tool.name: PseudoContourBH_Tool

param.name: outFeat
param.dialogReference: This is the output feature class delineates the bathymetric high features.

param.name: sDepth
param.dialogReference: The shallowest contour depth value for the mapping. The value must be negative or zero.

param.name: dDepth
param.dialogReference: The deepest contour depth value for the mapping. The value must be negative.

param.name: cInterval
param.dialogReference: The interval between contour lines. The value must be positive.

param.name: depthFactor
param.dialogReference: This parameter, together with the "Depth Difference Calculation Method" parameter, is used to calculate the "Depth Difference" threshold. If the "Depth Difference Calculation Method" is "As Absolute Depth Value (m)", enter a positive depth value to represent the "Depth Difference" threshold. If the "Depth Difference Calculation Method" is "As Percentage of the Contour Value (%)", enter a positive percentage value. If for example, a value of 5 is entered, the "Depth Difference" threshold is calculated as abs(5% * the contour value).

param.name: depthMethod
param.expression: As Absolute Depth Value (m) | As Percentage of the Contour Value (%)
param.dialogReference: Select one of the two methods from the drop-down list to calculate the "Depth Difference" threshold.

param.name: minAreaThreshold
param.dialogReference: The minimum threshold of polygon area. All resulted bathymetric high feature polygons should have areas greater than this threshold.

param.name: maxAreaThreshold
param.dialogReference: The maximum threshold of polygon area. All resulted bathymetric high feature polygons should have areas smaller than this threshold. The default value is one-third of the dataset area.

param.name: method
param.dialogReference: Select one of the two mapping algorithms from the drop-down list.

tool.summary:
This tool uses a pseudo contour based method to map bathymetric high features from bathymetry data. A bathymetric high feature is topographically above (or higher than) an enclosed contour. Because each bathymetric high feature may be intercepted or enclosed by multiple contours, the objective of the mapping is to identify the most likely enclosed contour as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature.

This tool creates pseudo contours at a selected depth using the Raster Con function. As a result, the pseudo contours are slightly different from the true contours created using the Vector Contour function because they follow the outer edges instead of the centres of raster cells. A drawback of the "Contour Tool Bathymetric High" tool is that it is unable to map those partial bathymetric high features that are cut off by the dataset boundary. This is because that the contours created using the Vector Contour function are not closed around these features. The pseudo contours created in this tool are able to form closed contours around these partial features and thus provide opportunities to map these partial bathymetric high features.

The followings are the key mapping steps:

  1. Determine the depth range (and thus the "Shallowest Contour Depth" and the "Deepest Contour Depth" parameters) within which the targeted bathymetric high features are located.

  2. Loop through each contour depth from the shallowest to the deepest and do the followings:

    • generate pseudo contours at the selected contour depth using the Raster Con function,

    • convert the enclosed pseudo contours at the selected contour depth to polygons,

    • select only those contour polygons with their areas greater than the "Minimum Area Threshold" parameter but smaller than the "Maximum Area Threshold" parameter,

    • eliminate all holes in the selected contour polygons,

    • calculate the mean depth of the selected contour polygons,

    • for each contour polygon, calculate the depth difference between its mean depth and the contour value, and

    • further select only those contour polygons that have positive depth difference greater than a threshold (calculated by the combination of the "Depth Difference" parameter and the "Depth Difference Calculation Method" parameter).

  3. Merge all of the selected contour polygons from all of the contour depths. Note that one bathymetric high feature may be intercepted or enclosed by one to multiple of these merged polygons.

  4. Determine how many contour(s) intercept or enclose each bathymetric high feature.

  5. If a bathymetric high feature is enclosed by only one contour polygon, select the contour polygon as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature.

  6. If a bathymetric high feature is intercepted or enclosed by two contour polygons, selected the contour polygon with a deeper contour as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature.

  7. If a bathymetric high feature is intercepted or enclosed by three or more contour polygons, the following procedures are used to determine the most likely contour polygon as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature:

    • generate a table with two columns: contour value and polygon area, each row lists the corresponding values of one intercepted or enclosed contour,

    • sort the rows using the contour values in a descending order (e.g., -40m, -50m and -60m, from the shallowest to the deepest),

    • if the "Mapping Method" parameter is "First Derivative", for each consecutive pair of neighbouring contour polygons (e.g., -40m and -50m, then -50m and -60m), calculate the first derivative (or slope) of the polygon area between two neighbouring contour polygons, and then

      • identify the index location of the maximum first derivative,

      • use the index location to split the contour values into two subsets,

      • select the subset with a higher number of elements (if two subsets have an identical number of elements, select the subset with deeper contour values), and

      • select the deepest contour within the selected subset as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature;

    • if the "Mapping Method" parameter is "Second Derivative", for each consecutive pair of neighbouring contour polygons (e.g., -40m and -50m, then -50m and -60m), calculate the first derivative (or slope) of the polygon area between two neighbouring contour polygons, then calculate the second derivative (or slope of slope) of the polygon area between two neighbouring contour polygons, and then

      • identify the index location of the maximum second derivative,

      • use the index location to split the contour values into two subsets,

      • select the subset with shallower contour values,

      • select the deepest contour within the selected subset as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature, and

      • note that if there are only three contours intercepting or enclosing the bathymetric high features, there is only one second derivative value, in this case, select the second deepest contour as the boundary of the bathymetric high feature.

  8. Loop through each bathymetric high feature, then merge all selected contour polygons from the merged contour polygons as the final "Output Bathymetric High Featureclass".

Note that the multiprocessing capability is used to speed up the processes described in the step 8 above.

scriptExample.para: This tool can not be called from Python script or Python command line window.

searchKeys.keyword: This tool maps bathymetric high features from a bathymetric data using a pseudo Contour based method.
